    <div class="prose-vt">
      <h2 id="shape">The shape of a syndicate</h2>
      <p>A syndicate is a host plus an audience plus a tournament. The host runs the show; the audience makes predictions; the tournament is the schedule of matches everyone is calling. Tournamental supplies the prediction game, the leaderboards, the 3D watch-along, the share cards, and (on premium) the CRM and the messaging.</p>
      <p>What you supply is the audience and, optionally, the prize. The audience can be anyone: customers, listeners, members, parents, colleagues, followers. The prize can be anything: a store voucher, a Bluetooth speaker, a season-ticket upgrade, a coffee subscription, bragging rights, or pooled entry fees. The platform does not care.</p>
      <p>Two rules:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Tournamental never touches money.</strong> On free, the host settles offline. On premium, the host's own Stripe-connected CRM handles paid entries.</li>
        <li><strong>Members must opt in</strong> before a sponsor sees their contact details. Aggregate stats (member count, country breakdown, leaderboard position) are visible to the host by default; personal contact details are not.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2 id="audiences">Six audience archetypes</h2>
      <p>Pick the closest archetype to your audience; mix and match the playbook elements as you need.</p>

      <h3 id="ecommerce">1. E-commerce store</h3>
      <p><strong>Audience.</strong> Your customer list, social followers, and email subscribers. They probably don't care about football.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it works.</strong> Six weeks of free engagement around something culturally enormous, with no obligation for the customer to be a "sports person". The prize is your product. Picks-saved is a daily check-in habit that translates into store visits.</p>
      <p><strong>Prize.</strong> $250 store voucher for the winner, $100 for second, $50 for third. Or a high-value product (your top SKU) for the winner only.</p>
      <p><strong>Where to put the widget.</strong> Homepage hero, dedicated landing page (yourstore.com/worldcup), order-confirmation thank-you page, and the post-purchase email. Customers who already bought something see "now play for $250 more".</p>
      <p><strong>Recruit copy (email subject lines that work):</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>"Predict the World Cup. Win $250 from us."</li>
        <li>"Six weeks of football. One shopping spree."</li>
        <li>"You don't need to know football. You just need a hunch."</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Week-by-week.</strong> Pre-tournament: launch with the email above. Group stage: daily leaderboard email to the top 25%; midweek to everyone. Knockouts: heavy push when picks change risk profile. Final: live leaderboard email morning-of, winner-announcement email evening-of.</p>

      <h3 id="radio">2. Radio station</h3>
      <p><strong>Audience.</strong> Daily listeners, the breakfast show in particular. Local, opinionated, primed for callbacks.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it works.</strong> The leaderboard is an on-air segment. The breakfast host calls out the top three every morning ("And in second place this morning, Karen from Mt Eden, last week she was at #47"). The prize-sponsor mention runs alongside.</p>
      <p><strong>Prize.</strong> Sponsor-funded. Typical package: a Bluetooth speaker, 12 months of coffee, a $500 gift card, or a hotel weekend. Total prize-pool value $1,000 to $3,000 is normal.</p>
      <p><strong>Sponsor pitch.</strong> "Six weeks of daily on-air mentions, your logo on every share card our listeners post, your brand baked into the morning leaderboard segment, and your contact list grows by every opt-in listener." See <a href="#sponsor-pitch">sponsor pitch templates</a>.</p>
      <p><strong>Where to put the widget.</strong> Station homepage hero, app home screen, dedicated landing page, and the email newsletter.</p>
      <p><strong>Recruit copy:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>"Predict every World Cup match. Win the prize pack. Live with us, on air, every morning."</li>
        <li>"The bracket is live. The breakfast crew has its picks in. Where are yours?"</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Week-by-week.</strong> Pre-tournament: 10 days of teaser drops, host-vs-host bracket reveals on air. Tournament: every morning, top three plus a "biggest climber". Final: live-from-the-pub broadcast for the winner.</p>

      <h3 id="football-club">3. Football club / supporters trust</h3>
      <p><strong>Audience.</strong> Members, season-ticket holders, supporters-trust subscribers, family-club newsletter list.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it works.</strong> The club already has the audience and the relationship. The tournament is a six-week reason for the relationship to mean something day-to-day. Picks-saved on the leaderboard is "we're all in this together".</p>
      <p><strong>Prize.</strong> Season-ticket upgrade, signed kit, a private box for the home opener, or a clubhouse-day prize-presentation event for the leader. Member-only, member-funded, member-rewarded.</p>
      <p><strong>Where to put the widget.</strong> Members' area of the club website, the matchday-programme PDF (link not embed), the supporters-trust newsletter, and the club app if there is one.</p>
      <p><strong>Recruit copy:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>"Members-only World Cup bracket. Top of the table wins a signed kit and a clubhouse-day presentation."</li>
        <li>"Your prediction history, on the same ledger as the senior squad's. Make us proud."</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Week-by-week.</strong> Pre-tournament: reveal the prize on a member-newsletter sequence. Tournament: weekly leaderboard email tied into the senior-squad's training-week digest. Final: prize presentation on a matchday or open-training day.</p>

      <h3 id="school">4. School fundraiser</h3>
      <p><strong>Audience.</strong> Parents, senior students, alumni, the local-business directory the school already taps for raffle prizes.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it works.</strong> Existing fundraising mechanics (silent auctions, sausage sizzles, raffle tickets) are tired. A six-week prediction game with a real prize is novel, the entry-fee maths is simple, and the kids participate. Sponsor logos on the leaderboard sell themselves.</p>
      <p><strong>Prize.</strong> Sponsor-donated. A local business or two donates the prize pack; the school keeps every dollar of the entry fees. Entry is typically $10 per person; 200 entries means $2,000 raised. The prize pack is whatever the sponsor wants to give (gift cards, services, a brand-new appliance).</p>
      <p><strong>Sponsor pitch.</strong> Same template as the radio station, scaled down: "Your logo on every leaderboard share, in every parent email for six weeks, and a thank-you mention at prize-giving."</p>
      <p><strong>Where to put the widget.</strong> School newsletter (embed if the newsletter is web; link if PDF), school website members area, classroom-display screen if there is one.</p>
      <p><strong>Recruit copy:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>"Predict the World Cup, $10 entry, all proceeds to the school's new sports gear. Sponsored prize pack from [local business] for the winner."</li>
        <li>"Get the senior students teaching the parents how to use the bracket builder. They love it."</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Week-by-week.</strong> Pre-tournament: launch in the school newsletter two weeks out. Tournament: weekly progress email plus a midweek "still time to join" reminder. Final: prize-giving at the next assembly or end-of-term event.</p>

      <h3 id="workplace">5. Workplace bracket</h3>
      <p><strong>Audience.</strong> Your colleagues. The number is small (dozens), the engagement is daily, the chat is a Slack or Teams channel.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it works.</strong> The workplace bracket is one of the oldest sweepstake formats in the world. The improvement Tournamental makes is the predictions live somewhere shared, scoring is automatic, arguments end, and the bracket is on the company intranet rather than a spreadsheet someone has to maintain.</p>
      <p><strong>Prize.</strong> Pooled entry fees, $10 to $20 per person. Or pooled by the company as a fully-funded prize (some workplaces do this to avoid any gambling-flavoured optics).</p>
      <p><strong>Where to put the widget.</strong> Intranet front page, Slack / Teams pinned post (link to the syndicate page), or the "social club" page if there is one.</p>
      <p><strong>Recruit copy:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>"World Cup bracket. $10 entry. Winner gets the lot. Sign up before kickoff."</li>
        <li>"This year we are using Tournamental, no more spreadsheet, no more arguments."</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Week-by-week.</strong> Pre-tournament: one Slack post and a calendar invite for the kick-off morning huddle. Tournament: a daily auto-post of the leaderboard in the channel (the embed widget has a daily-digest webhook). Final: prize-giving at the end-of-tournament team lunch.</p>

      <h3 id="creator">6. Creator / influencer</h3>
      <p><strong>Audience.</strong> Your followers, your subscribers, your newsletter list, your Discord, your community.</p>
      <p><strong>Why it works.</strong> Followers want a reason to spend time with you, and the bracket is six weeks of that. The leaderboard is content; every climber and faller is a story; the share cards are pre-built social posts your followers will already make.</p>
      <p><strong>Prize.</strong> Sponsored. One brand-deal underwrites the whole tournament's content output. The sponsor's logo is on the embed, the share cards, and the prize.</p>
      <p><strong>Sponsor pitch.</strong> "I'm running a World Cup bracket for [N] followers. Six weeks of daily content with your logo on every share. Audience is [demographics]. Prize budget I'd like covered: $X. I keep [Y] as a sponsor fee."</p>
      <p><strong>Where to put the widget.</strong> Your link-in-bio page (Linktree alternative, hosted by you), the homepage of your site, the newsletter, the Discord welcome message.</p>
      <p><strong>Recruit copy:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>"The bracket is live. Beat me, I'll send you the prize. Beat my mum, I'll be impressed."</li>
        <li>"Predict every match. Climb the leaderboard. Win [sponsor prize]. Sponsored by [brand], who get every credit they deserve."</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Week-by-week.</strong> Pre-tournament: announcement post, sponsor reveal, opening-fixtures pick reveal. Tournament: a daily climbers-and-fallers post; one "I called it" or "I called it wrong" video per round. Final: prize handover content with the sponsor.</p>

      <h2 id="prize-structures">Prize structures that work</h2>

      <h3>Winner-takes-all</h3>
      <p>One prize, one winner. Best for high-value prizes ($500+) and any audience where "everyone is in with a shot until the final whistle" is the appeal. Simplest narrative; easiest sponsor pitch.</p>

      <h3>Podium (1st, 2nd, 3rd)</h3>
      <p>Three prizes of decreasing value. Keeps mid-table players engaged because second and third are still meaningful. Best for audiences over ~50 members where winner-takes-all would feel like a lottery.</p>

      <h3>Tiered (top 10%, top 25%, top 50%)</h3>
      <p>Smaller prizes for larger groups, e.g. top-10% get a discount code, top-25% get a smaller code, everyone in the top half gets a thank-you bundle. Best for very large audiences (1,000+) where individual prizes don't scale.</p>

      <h3>Random-draw among top half</h3>
      <p>Make the leaderboard cut, get into the draw. Mixes prediction skill with chance and tends to feel friendlier than pure skill ladders. Good for fundraisers because more people feel rewarded.</p>

      <h3>Sponsored bundle</h3>
      <p>A package of items from several sponsors (e.g. Bluetooth speaker from one, coffee subscription from another, a $100 gift card from a third). Higher perceived value than a single prize, and three logos rather than one.</p>

      <h3>Pooled entry money</h3>
      <p>Every entrant pays in; the pool is the prize. Best for workplaces, friend groups, and clubs. Tournamental does not handle the cash; the host pools it offline (free tier) or via Stripe inside their own CRM sub-account (premium tier).</p>

      <h2 id="sponsor-pitch">Sponsor pitch templates</h2>

      <p>If you are running a sponsor-funded syndicate, the pitch needs to translate "six weeks of daily engagement on a global cultural event" into something a brand manager can put in front of their boss. Two templates that work:</p>

      <h3>Template A: the radio / creator pitch</h3>
      <p><strong>Subject:</strong> "Six-week World Cup engagement campaign for [your audience]"</p>
      <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-accent-500 pl-4 my-4">
        <p>Hi [name],</p>
        <p>I'm running a six-week World Cup prediction game for [my audience: N listeners / followers / members]. Audience is [demographics + locations]. Every member sees a leaderboard with your logo on it every time they check it, plus a share card with your logo every time they climb. We expect [N] saved picks across the tournament and [N] share-card prints.</p>
        <p>Looking for a sponsor for the prize pack and the brand placement. Total package $[X]; prize budget within that is $[Y]. I'd love to put your brand on this. Are you free for a 15-minute call this week?</p>
        <p>[Your name]</p>
      </blockquote>

      <h3>Template B: the school / non-profit pitch</h3>
      <p><strong>Subject:</strong> "Prize donation for the [School] World Cup fundraiser"</p>
      <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-accent-500 pl-4 my-4">
        <p>Hi [name],</p>
        <p>[School] is running a World Cup prediction-game fundraiser this year. Parents and senior students enter for $10 each; all proceeds go to [cause: new sports gear / library books / the music programme]. We expect [N] entries, raising approximately $[X].</p>
        <p>We're looking for a local business to donate the winner's prize pack. Your logo would be on every leaderboard share, in every parent email for six weeks, and you'd get a thank-you mention at prize-giving in front of [audience size]. Anything from a gift card to a product bundle works.</p>
        <p>Could you spare 10 minutes this week to chat?</p>
        <p>[Your name]</p>
      </blockquote>

      <h2 id="run-of-show">Six-week run-of-show</h2>

      <p>Cadence matters more than copy. A syndicate that goes quiet between matchdays evaporates; a syndicate with a daily rhythm carries its audience all the way to the final whistle.</p>

      <h3>Weeks -2 to -1 (lead-in)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Announce the syndicate with the prize headline.</li>
        <li>Open sign-ups. Embed the widget on at least three pages of your site.</li>
        <li>Sponsor reveal (if applicable). Press release if the audience is big enough.</li>
        <li>Pin the bracket page in your most-used channel.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Week 1 (group stage opens)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Welcome email: "the bracket is open, the first match is tonight, here's how to pick".</li>
        <li>Daily leaderboard digest from day 2 onwards. Top 10 + biggest climber + biggest faller.</li>
        <li>Midweek "still time to join" push to anyone who saw the launch but didn't sign up.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Weeks 2-3 (group stage continues)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Maintain the daily digest cadence.</li>
        <li>Weekly "round of 16 is coming, lock in your knockout bracket" reminder.</li>
        <li>Sponsor-mention email at the midpoint thanking them for the prize.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Weeks 4-5 (knockouts)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Stakes rise. Send a "your favourite is one match away" alert to anyone whose champion-pick is in the next round.</li>
        <li>Switch from daily digest to per-match alerts for matches with the highest leaderboard impact.</li>
        <li>"What if?" content: "if [team] win tonight, here's how the leaderboard reshuffles."</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Week 6 (final)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Final-morning email: "today is the day, here's where you stand".</li>
        <li>Live-leaderboard hero on the homepage from kickoff to the trophy lift.</li>
        <li>Winner-announcement email within an hour of the final whistle, with the share-card image attached.</li>
        <li>Sponsor thank-you email and prize-handover content within 48 hours.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Week 7 (after)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Recap email or post: top 10, the best calls, the biggest comeback.</li>
        <li>"Save the date" tease for the next tournament you'll run (Six Nations, Cricket World Cup, the next FIFA cycle).</li>
        <li>If premium: keep the CRM list warm with off-tournament content. The syndicate is a list now.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="premium">When to upgrade to premium</h2>

      <p>The free tier covers everything a smaller host needs. Upgrade to premium when one of the following is true:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>You want paid entries</strong> and don't want to handle the cash via PayPal links and goodwill. Premium gives you Stripe Checkout inside your own CRM sub-account; the funds settle to your bank, not ours.</li>
        <li><strong>You want to send SMS or WhatsApp at scale.</strong> Free tier members can opt in to Tournamental's own match-day alerts; premium gives you your own outbound messaging through your own number, branded in your name.</li>
        <li><strong>You want a real CRM</strong> with workflows, nurture sequences, segmentation, A/B-tested email subject lines, lead-scoring, and the rest. Premium provisions a HighLevel sub-account; we configure it for your tournament and hand you the keys.</li>
        <li><strong>You want the subdomain.</strong> Premium hosts get yourname.tournamental.com as a full-page experience for people who want more than an embed.</li>
        <li><strong>You want your own brand on every surface.</strong> Premium removes the Tournamental footer from the widget and the subdomain.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>$97/month plus messaging usage. Cancel any time. We provision the CRM on day one; you keep the contact list when you leave.</p>

      <h2 id="next">Ready to start</h2>
      <p>The fastest path is to <a href="/start" class="link">claim a syndicate path</a>, drop the widget on one of your pages, and run a small test syndicate with friends or colleagues for a weekend. Then scale up the audience when you have the rhythm of the daily digest dialled in. The full <a href="/syndicates#pricing" class="link">pricing page</a> covers what the free and premium tiers include.</p>
    </div>
